Gent mr. van Espelgen
Reg en ul van gisteren in mij wel gewoorden, & met blijckap verstaen dat ul wederon en
den ontfanck is van de canten, 3od geeve dat alles haest in ul handen magh wesen op
dat, t eorder, ul hier mogen sien. mr Rosseau van Brussel schrijft als dat tot mobeuse
door een ulaemsch nouwe een partije canten te loof gebroght sijn, die gesuponeert woorden
van d'ons te wesen, soo heeft hij daer over alle mogelijcke gecharchie doen doen, om
daer aghter te geraecken, aen en tusten scq hope van ul morgen breerder te vernemen in
dat ul sijn pas. nogh wat anle gebruycken
a 22d.

Ils seront depechez d'main a niewporte a mr. Valligo pour sumine vos ord, les 3-
precedentes sont la bien arrivée le 20, selon s'aduys de 20, j'espere d vous voire
appres dimain, & e forter de bones novelles de Gant, car mr. van Espelgem m'at aflait
du hier qu'il qlque pieces de denteleir, & qu'il attandet, la peu grande

Londen Mon Edmond larner
Antwarp 27 Janu 1672
S my last to you was on the 21 curr., sence non from you, whilst I have been
imployed in the concernes att Gant, & recovered about ƒ300- valew more in laces, & one of the
cheef anitens in floyd att megelen where he hath his wife, & whether an other of the interressed
goeth this day, haveing procured an order of our governor to take him, his wife or any thing
whent be longs to him, which if doth suceed well will help us to all or most the goods: I am
a putting in onder what belongs to you, to send itt you p first, besides there is 2 packetts ready
to come by our fridayes messenger, butt they cont. butt some what imord then one of the formarly
they beeng made up, according to a new dircchen need of late from London, of othr freinds
which I fancy to be vere good & more convenient for importing, The invoyce you shall have
a saturday, the whole order is not nitt yett ready, wants about ⅓ part, which I exspect in
this week, so that all will be dispasch in time, God in heaven will send all'in safetye
wanting some monij have drawne this day on you £100- a 35.3 att 1½ vto payable to
the order of m. Leonard vermeulen, pray give all due honour to my bill, I could finde no
better opportunitie, so hope itt is to yd content: I exspect these laces I now bought, & buy
so cheap that theij will never be so cheap againe, for I pay y. all with mony upon
the nas, & do presume that within they will rise againe - wee have sustered vere
much yeasterday by a violent storme, which doth shill continew, & hath drowned al the
bands here about, wee much feare for hollant & zealand for such a flood, was never seen
god confort all loyers, for I doubt itt will cost much valeu & lives
C 27 ditto
London mr. Abram Bivian
mij last to you was on the 14th curtt sence non from you att which I do not a little wonder
for you snon itt is nott for my or yd creditt bo draw on you, & yett you advise mee not one
word, wat to do, withiun ⅓ is £150- more 30 pay, & to discharge the £200 - have been
sorceed to draw on my other freinds, I assure you, I never exspected such manner of
bealing from you, & vather I sould suster any the like, would desist, I never list you behinde
for my accott, I do nott know what reeson you have so do do, principally this time a yeare
when there is no mony ssiring I exspect my acctt. curtt. & pnext I shall not faile to send
yd II hope you negleett nothing in dispatching the in ordered bayes
C28 Jan
Londen mr. Roger Jonds
Icq benerwondert wat ul doet m reusegem comt mij betalinge wages over de roy lakens
van Timas Seaman aen mij gelevert, die liggen hier nogh want sij sijn niet verkoop ofte leverbaer
gelijcq ul heb ges. en begeers die absoluet voor mijne reeq niet, nie de selve aengaen ofte
niet, can ul probeeren dat de selve u sijn, & seaman niet toebehoorden, icq will niet tegen
de reden gaen, maer icq il die evenwel niet voor mijne recq betalen, want die sijn niet leverbaer
Icq hebonder u adres aen Seaman gef. waerom en antw. hij mijnen brief niet, soo wel als
dan ul hem heeft doen schrijven aen mij over t' gene icq aen ul selfs had ges. 't gene icq
van hem moet hebben is voor reeq van m wilt. Pindar in Londen
C 28 det

and hath been m. Roger Sonds his servant, as much as I perceave he doth not intend to returne
